1. Combined Scatter Plot: Advertising vs EPS (Yearly)
Insight: Weak to moderate positive relationship overall; varies by company
What the chart shows:
Each dot = one company's yearly advertising spend vs its calculated annual EPS.
Each coloured line = regression trend per company.
Key insights:
PG (Procter & Gamble) and PEP (PepsiCo) show a positive slope â†’ higher ad spend is generally associated with slightly higher EPS.
KMB (Kimberly-Clark) also shows a positive correlation, though weaker.
KO (Coca-Cola) shows a slightly negative slope, suggesting that years with higher marketing spend do not immediately translate into higher EPS for KO.
CL (Colgate-Palmolive) also shows a mild negative trend â†’ marketing spend might depress margins short-term.
Overall interpretation:
Across all firms, there is no uniform relationship â€” advertising helps some companies grow EPS, but for others, EPS dips in heavy advertising years due to higher expenses.

2. Normalized Time-Series (Z-Scores): Advertising vs EPS Over Time (Yearly)
Insight: Advertising spikes often lead EPS trends, but the relationship is not perfectly aligned across companies.
This chart compares standardized advertising spend vs EPS over 2019â€“2021 for each company.
CL (Colgate-Palmolive)
Advertising spikes in 2021, EPS also peaks â€” same direction, strong alignment.
In 2020 both ad spend and EPS were lower â†’ consistent pattern.
Advertising and EPS move in the same direction, suggesting a positive connection.
KMB (Kimberly-Clark)
Ad spend drops sharply in 2020; EPS also declines â†’ aligned movement.
Both spike again in 2021.
Clear positive relationship over time.
KO (Coca-Cola)
Advertising increases in 2021, but EPS declines.
Earlier years show opposite patterns.
KO displays a negative relationship, meaning advertising spikes may occur during challenging years to defend market share, not to drive immediate EPS.
PEP (PepsiCo)
Advertising jumps in 2020; EPS rises in the following year.
EPS lags behind ad spend changes.
Possible lag effect: marketing investments may boost future EPS, not the same year's EPS.
PG (Procter & Gamble)
Advertising peaks in 2020; EPS also highest that year â†’ aligned.
Both fall in 2021.
Strong year-on-year positive alignment, suggesting effective marketing ROI.
Time-series takeaway:
Most companies show advertising and EPS moving in the same direction, except Coca-Cola, which behaves differently (possibly due to restructuring or pandemic disruptions).

